    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-03-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-03-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="16"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d16">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                        Koerner</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 72.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-03-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 12, 1864</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi>Your interesting despatch of the 14th of February,
                    No. 76, has been received.</p>
                <p>The war in St. Domingo is an affair which can be considered by this government
                    only with reference to the duties and obligations of the United States as a
                    member of the family of nations. The revolutionists in that island have, in
                    various forms and through several channels, appealed to this government for
                    recognition, for aid, and for sympathy. Pursuing the policy we have too
                    ineffectually insisted upon at the hands of other nations, we have not received
                    any agents of the revolution, even informally, nor have we in any way responded
                    to them, while we have given instructions to ministerial officers to see that
                    the neutrality laws of the United States are regularly maintained and
                    enforced.</p>
                <p>You must have already received instructions from this department to submit
                    certain claims of American citizens against her Catholic Majesty’s government
                    for redress for injuries and losses sustained by them, as they represent, in the
                    military operations which have taken place on the island. Those instructions <pb
                        facs="0037" n="13" xml:id="pg_13"/> indicate with sufficient clearness, it
                    is hoped, the manner in which the claims are to be presented. It is thought
                    inexpedient to authorize any concert with the representatives of other powers in
                    presenting or prosecuting the claims.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gustavus Koerner</hi>, Esq., &amp;<hi rend="italic"
                            >c</hi>., &amp;<hi rend="italic">c</hi>., &amp;<hi rend="italic"
                            >c</hi>.<hi rend="italic">, Madrid.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
